<font color="#FF0000">ROOTS OF THE MATTER</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 21 13:44:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Okay, here we go... one more expert opinion on PTSD.  I hope that eighteen years of happy, youthful memories in a good home, thirteen years of honorable military service, two years of intensive combat, three years as a hobo, eight years in two fine universities and thirty one troubled years of seeking, qualifies me to say something meaningful to the most special people on Earth...my Brothers of Choice.<br><br>
There is something mystic about this coming together of wisdom from so many different directions.  Each of you are pointing toward the center.  All of you bring something so pure and powerful.  The Gestaltic result will definitely be greater that the sum of its parts.<br><br>
Near the beginning, the Creator gave man the pipe... a symbolic gesture that man should become tranquil in his approach to visit with the true Father.  Because all men are different... each would come away with a different perspective.  And God gave man the Sacred Drum...where a circle would form around this nucleus and mankind would share their thoughts on their revelations...in a serious manner.<br><br>
These are my thoughts that I hold up before you... for you to consider... for you to reject or accept... embellish or condense... to embrace or throw to the ground.<br><br>
I do not like to address symptoms except to aid me in the search for cause.  I prefer to eliminate the cause rather than treat the symptoms.  I endeavor to factor until there is no lower level to explore.  Also, I love the saying, &quot;Keep it simple, Stupid!&quot;<br><br>
What I discuss pertains to all people... regardless of cultural diversity, gender, age, socio-economic level or any other identity.  The only qualifying criteria to suffer PTSD is that you be a human being.<br><br>
It is not an over simplification that there are only two things every person seeks from the womb to the grave... avoid pain and gain pleasure.  I propose, for you to consider, that the greatest pleasure is acceptance... if that is true... then the greatest pain is rejection.  Early in life, when we were pre-verbal and pre-logical we found the greatest pleasure in evacuating our bowels and bladders with a very simple focus upon relief that gave pleasure.  Very soon we learned that we would postpone those pleasures to gain the &quot;Big&quot; one.  That acceptance from Mom and Dad for being a good little boy or girl and using the potty.  It was the elementary beginning of delay of gratification.  We would perform in certain ways, for the rest of our lives, to gain acceptance.<br><br>
I believe that we are a composite of two major areas of mental activity...Cognition and Affect... or simply thinking and feeling.  John Locke said, &quot;Ergo Cogito Sum,&quot; You are the sum of your thoughts.  In the same vein, George Berkeley offered, &quot;Esse percipi es,&quot; You are what you perceive.  Cognition and affect or thinking and feeling are inversely proportional... the more you are a thinker the less you are a feeler and vice versa... and we slide back and forth on the scale.  It is like having a basket full of apples and oranges.  The more apples you have in the basket.. the less room for oranges... the more oranges you have the fewer apples.<br><br>
Thoughts give direction for feelings (emotions).  If you think good, positive thoughts the resultant feelings are good.  If you think negative thoughts...the feelings are bad.  It is the same with feelings!  If you are feeling good feelings, your thoughts seem to follow along... and conversely, if you are feeling low... your thoughts seem to center on darkness.  It is not unlike a dog chasing his tail.  But, a word of caution... thoughts have handles on them and feelings don't... trying to capture an emotion is akin to capturing a greasy pig.  Ancient wisdom advises us to &quot;capture each thought&quot; not capture each feeling or emotion!<br><br>
Thoughts can overwhelm emotions.  We are able to shut the world of feelings out.  We can become catatonic and stare at the wall with no feelings.... sit on an Alice pack in the pouring rain and try to smoke a wet cigarette and utter statements like &quot;it don't matter anymore.&quot;  We can orchestrate our lives to be filled with important stuff that commands our attention every waking minute... we don't have time to be feelers.. We must think serious thoughts...we become workaholics.. Inattentive to our children.. wives..and the people around us.  Essentially, we lose our interpersonal relationship skills.  We &quot;control&quot; or at least attempt to control with thought.<br><br>
Emotions can overwhelm thinking (cognition).  We are more inclined to be emotional... I don't want to think!  Thoughts carry me to horrible places.  I choose instead, to be angry, sad or laughing my ass off.  And here is where the big difference comes in...every emotion is based upon FEAR!  I challenge you to present a feeling that is not fear manifesting or motivated.  You may say love is not fear...think about it.  What kind of fear is generated when you really love someone?<br>
What do you feel when you place the first grader on the school bus?  Doubts and jealousies emanate from the fear that you are not totally secure in your relationship with others you love... perhaps more visible in romantic, sexual relationships.<br><br>
Here comes another strong statement: Every fear that you can imagine revolves around control!<br><br>
I will break here to allow input and response... I want to get heavy on control.
